This is the player handbook for my campaigns. We play classic D\&D
using rules from the early eighties.\marginnote{Ownership of the rules
  is optional. If you want to dig deeper, I recommend
  \href{http://www.rpgnow.com/product/110274/DD-Basic-Set-Rulebook-B-X-ed-Basic}{Basic
    D\&D by Moldvay} and
  \href{http://www.rpgnow.com/product/110792/DD-Expert-Set-Rulebook-B-X-ed-Basic}{Expert
    D\&D by Cook} (from the early eighties),
  \href{https://necroticgnome.com/}{Old-School Essentials}
  (compatible, with new layout) or
  \href{http://goblinoidgames.com/index.php/downloads/}{Labyrinth
    Lord} (free).} My campaigns usually last for around fifty short
sessions of around two hours each and end before player characters
reach level ten, which is why the information for higher level player
characters is missing.

The rules offer \textbf{very little mechanics}: there aren't many
classes to choose from, no feats, no prestige classes and hardly any
special abilities or skills, no magic items for sale. Furthermore,
elves, dwarves and halflings are simply separate classes. There are no
elven thieves or dwarven mages. On the other hand, fewer rules also
leave \textbf{a lot of freedom} for players. The characters are as
diplomatic, friendly or intimidating as the players want them to be.

We're playing in a
\href{http://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/WideOpenSandbox}{sandbox}.
There is \textbf{no planned ending} for the campaign. The actions of
player characters determines the directions the campaign grows
in.\marginnote{Players determine where the campaign will head. If
  player characters investigate rumors and locations, I will develop
  the game world in that direction. The harder you look, the more
  there is to see.}

There are \textbf{no clerics} in my game and I use \textbf{restricted
  spell acquisition} for magic users and elves: finding scrolls and
spell books does not allow you to master those spells. You need a
teacher. At the same time, the slow introduction of new spells change
the game over time. This is a journey \textbf{from zero to hero}.

To keep fights interesting (and short), the more dangerous monsters
use poison, level drain, spells, and other \textbf{save or die}
effects.

Dangers are not adapted to the strength of the party. Generally
speaking it's safer near civilized settlements. The further you move
into the wilderness, the more dangerous it is. That's how
\textbf{players control the risks they want to take}.

Preparation and experience should help you avoid situations, where
your character's survival depends on a single die roll.\marginnote{The
  game will remain dangerous for a long time. At very low levels
  limited hit points mean you'll die if you get hit. Later, around
  level five and six, it's still easy to die because of spells like
  \emph{fireball} or \emph{lightning bolt}, poisonous critters and
  petrifying gases, or level drain. At higher level, when the first
  characters hit level eight and nine, the game will be less dangerous
  and involve more reaction rolls and larger battles, but then again,
  the characters will soon retire from adventuring…} If you're rolling
dice, it's already too late. \textbf{A saving throw is your last
  chance} to survive due to luck and experience. Ideally you would
never have to roll dice because you're well informed and well equipped.
Perseus didn't have to save against the medusa's petrifying gaze
because \emph{he was well prepared}.

\textbf{Followers are another safeguard against character death}:
torch bearers, men-at-arms and war dogs all cost money, but they will
also keep your character alive. Should player characters die, the next
character is most probably going to be one of their
\hyperref[sec:followers]{followers}.

\textbf{Experience points} are gained by defeating opponents and by
\textbf{spending gold} you gained on adventures.\marginnote{Spending
  gold on public \hyperref[sec:buildings]{buildings} is one way of
  spending a lot of money.} If you manage to obtain the gold without
combat, good for you. The best strategy is to pick your battles and
stack the odds in your favor as far as possible. Remember, if you're
rolling dice, it's already too late.

