\section{Basic Rules}
\label{sec:basicrules}

Some key terms, first.

\key{Player}: The people sitting at the table, you, me, our friends.

\key{Player Character}: The people we’re playing. My character is
called Edrig and hails from Einaheim.

\key{Experience Points} (\key{XP}): Defeating opponents grants
experience points, and spending money nets you \emph{one experience
  point per gold piece spent}. Examples: donations to a temple,
erecting a statue, organizing a party, building a manor house, hiring
servants, and so on. With enough experience points characters gain new
levels.\marginnote[-6em]{As gold turns into experience, the pursuit of
  treasure is a central element of adventures. But note that sometimes
  the simple act of bringing the loot back to safety can be a problem
  if you are weakened and heavily loaded on your way back to town.}
Gold (and thus XP) can be passed to other characters as long as the
recipient's level is \emph{the same or lower}.

\key{Level}: As time passes, characters hit better, get better saving
throws and gain hit points. They \emph{gain a level}.

\key{Hit Points}: Hit points indicate your endurance, luck and will to
live.\marginnote{Hit points are a measure of how much of a beating a
  character can take.} As you \emph{gain} a level, roll as many dice
as you have levels and keep the result if it is is \emph{higher} than
your current hit point total. Fighters and dwarves use a d8, magic
users and thieves use a d4, everybody else uses a d6. Do not forget to
add your constitution bonus to every die rolled. If your constitution
bonus is negative, you'll still get at least 1 hit point for every
die. If you \emph{lose} a level, roll as many dice as you have levels
and keep the result if it is \emph{lower} than your current hit point
total.

