\section{\index{Combat}Combat}
\label{sec:combat}

\key{Surprise}: Both sides roll a d6. Your side is surprised if you
roll a 1 or a 2. If you're surprised, you'll have to skip the first
round.

\key{Initiative}: At the beginning of every round, both sides roll a
d6.\marginnote{The worst that can happen is that opponents go twice in
  a row.} The higher number begins. On a tie, players begin.

\key{Round}: Every round, you can move and still do something before
or after your move.\marginnote{Anything may be \emph{attempted}, but
  chances of success and the time it takes will be determined at the
  table based on circumstances.} Typical \index{Action}actions: melee
or ranged attack, casting a spell, read a \index{Scroll}scroll, quaff
a \index{Potion}potion. \index{Getting Up}Getting up also counts as a
move. Dropping items you're holding, drawing a weapon or saying things
are free.

\key{To-Hit}: Roll a twenty-sided die (d20). Add the to-hit bonus
based on your level.\marginnote{The description of your class comes
  with a table with the to-hit bonus depending on your level.} Add the
armour class of your opponent. Add your strength bonus when making a
\index{Melee Attack}melee attack. Add your dexterity bonus when making
a \index{Ranged Attack}ranged attack. Add any magic bonuses, if you
have a magic weapon. If the sum is 20 or more,\marginnote{This is
  Delta's \href{http://www.oedgames.com/target20/}{Target 20} system.}
you hit.

\key[20, natural]{20}: If you roll a 20, you always hit and you do max
damage.

\key[30-sided die]{30}: Every player may use the thirty-sided die
(d30) in place of a d20 once per session. When rolling to hit, every
roll of twenty and above is a critical hit.

\key{Damage}: If you hit, roll damage using a d6.\marginnote{We don't
  use variable weapon damage. All weapons do 1d6 damage.} Add your
strength bonus when making a melee attack. There is no bonus for
ranged attacks.

\key{Shield}: When carrying a shield\marginnote{At low levels, shields
  are crucial! Unfortunately, thieves and magic users may not carry
  shields.} and hit by a melee weapon or a magical force such as a
lightning bolt or a fire ball, you may sacrifice the shield such that
it absorbs all damage and is destroyed.

\key{Space}: In a wide corridor (\unit[10]{ft}) three people can fight
side by side. The space required depends on the weapons used, however:
\marginnote{A typical setup would be four fighters in the front row
  with short swords or hand axes, four fighters in the second row with
  pole arms, and the rest in the back, shooting arrows and slinging
  stones.}

